    "section_help_text_M6Widi": {
      "type": "section-help-text",
      "name": "section-help-text",
      "settings": {
        "title": "A straight-talking guide to grip, latex, and why wear is part of the job.",
        "description": "<p class=\"section-help-text__text\">If you're here because your gloves are wearing down quicker than you expected — this page is for you.</p>\n<p class=\"section-help-text__text\">You're not alone. It’s one of the most common questions we get from keepers and parents:</p>\n<div class=\"questions-section\">\n<div class=\"question-card\">\n<p class=\"question-text\">“Why are the palms peeling?”</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"question-card\">\n<p class=\"question-text\">“Is this a defect?”</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"question-card\">\n<p class=\"question-text\">“They’ve only been used 3 times — is this normal?”</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p class=\"section-help-text__text\">Let’s set the record straight.</p>"
      }
    },
    "section_help_content_pYec3t": {
      "type": "section-help-content",
      "blocks": {
        "row_m3tbYp": {
          "type": "row",
          "settings": {
            "content-title": "How to measure your child’s hand",
            "content-description": "<p class=\"section-content__text\">If your gloves are showing signs of wear after just a few sessions, that doesn’t mean they’re faulty.</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">It means the latex is doing what it was designed to do: grip.</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">Latex is a soft, high-performance material. The stickier it is, the more fragile it becomes. That’s the trade-off.</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">Better grip = softer latex = faster wear.</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">That’s how it works. Always has.</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">If you’re using match-quality gloves (like ours), expect visible wear from the first few sessions — especially if you’re playing on turf, diving aggressively, or using poor recovery technique.</p>",
            "content-image": "shopify://shop_images/DSC8186.jpg",
            "content-isadaptive": true
          }
        },
        "row_KY74D7": {
          "type": "row",
          "settings": {
            "content-title": "How wear happens(and why it’s not a problem)",
            "content-description": "<p class=\"section-content__text\">Latex wears down through friction — not time.</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">It’s the constant impact, catching, diving, pushing off the ground, and recovering that breaks it down.</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">What does normal wear look like?</p>\n<ul class=\"section-content__list\">\n<li class=\"section-content__elem\">Peeling on the palms</li>\n<li class=\"section-content__elem\">Flattening of the latex texture</li>\n<li class=\"section-content__elem\">Abrasions on the fingertips</li>\n<li class=\"section-content__elem\">Small nicks or surface tears where you push off</li>\n<li class=\"section-content__elem\">Faster wear on one glove (usually your dominant hand)</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">None of this means the grip is gone. In fact, our gloves perform until there’s almost nothing left on the palm. You’ll often see keepers using a heavily worn pair and still catching clean — because it’s about feel, not looks.</p>",
            "content-image": "shopify://shop_images/MPH-02270.jpg",
            "content-isadaptive": true
          }
        },
        "row_hxwQzW": {
          "type": "row",
          "settings": {
            "content-title": "Why you can have two identical pairs — and one wears faster",
            "content-description": "<p class=\"section-content__text\">This is something we hear a lot:</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">“I’ve got two pairs of the same model. One’s fine. The other’s wearing fast. What gives?”</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">Here’s why:</p>\n<ul class=\"section-content__list\">\n<li class=\"section-content__elem\">You might train more in one than the other</li>\n<li class=\"section-content__elem\">You may dive harder on one surface (turf vs grass)</li>\n<li class=\"section-content__elem\">You’re using different recovery habits depending on fatigue</li>\n<li class=\"section-content__elem\">One hand takes more impact (your dominant side will wear faster)</li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">Same glove. Different context. Different wear.</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">This is why we always recommend separating gloves by use: One pair for matches. One for training. Even if they’re the same model — different usage = different lifespan.</p>",
            "content-image": "shopify://shop_images/MPH01490.jpg",
            "content-isadaptive": true
          }
        },
        "row_EpUdiM": {
          "type": "row",
          "settings": {
            "content-title": "Technique matters.Especially for junior keepers.",
            "content-description": "<p class=\"section-content__text\">No one likes to hear it, but it’s true:</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">A huge amount of wear — especially in youth gloves — comes down to poor technique.</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">If a keeper is dragging their palms when they stand up, diving hands-first onto turf, or landing flat on the latex — it’ll shred fast. That’s not a glove fault. That’s part of learning.</p>\n<p class=\"section-content__text\">That’s why we use Giga latex on all our junior models — it’s more durable, less prone to tearing, and built to help younger keepers develop without destroying gloves every other session.</p>",
            "content-image": "shopify://shop_images/MPH00188.jpg",
            "content-isadaptive": true
          }
        }
      },
